fp|1|cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|
at|^b@2

When your left-hand opponent opens the bidding and your partner doubles, it shows support (at least Hxx) for any 
unbid Major, shortness in the suit that she doubled, and an opening hand (or very very close to it).
So, let's see: LHO and partner have opening bids, leaving perhaps 14 points total for you and RHO.. 
If your RHO passes, then you have 2 choices: to bid or to pass. 

Let us see what you need to ^*upass^*n partner's double: 
You need to have a lot of trump tricks, AND no fit for partner's Major.

Example: LHO opened 1@h, your pard doubled, and RHO passes: 1@h  X   pass   ??
You have @sx   @HKQ1098   @dAxx   @cJxxx 
This is a MINIMUM hand for passing the double of 1 of a Major, converting partner's Take-out X into a penalty.
Notice... you do not have a Major-suit fit... 

BabsG:  Does this have anything to do with the Rule of  9?
mitche: No.. it has to do with Ron Klinger's rule of 10 and 12  
We will be discussing that shortly and you can find it online at bridgehands.com.|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|

Basically the rule of 10 and 12 is: 
- the length of your trump suit plus the level of the contract must be at least 12 (rule of 12)
- And the number of trump winners in your hand + level is at least 10.

So here: You have a misfit and the balance of power: 
- you have 3 sure trump-winners (KQ109) and the opponents are contracting for 7 tricks  => meets rule of 10)
- you have 5 trumps + 7 trick contract level = 12 => meets the rule of 12.
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|fp|1|
at|^b@2

Clearly, the higher the level, the fewer trumps and tricks you need to pass a take-out X.  

Most of the time you will want to bid over partner's TO double
So here is the general idea: bid your longest suit other than the one bid by LHO
Example: 1@h  X  pass  ??   
You have @sxxxx  @hxxx  @dJxx  @cQxx 
You MUST bid, so you bid 1@s, your longest suit.|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|

If I have a 4-card Major and a 5-card minor, it depends on scoring method, to an extent.
At anything but matchpoints, bid your longest suit (generally), but prefer your 4-card Major at MP's
or if your Major has better "texture"
Remember, your pard will probably lead your suit if the other side wins the contract.. 
Do not hang him by bidding 2@C when you have @sKJxx,@hxxx,@Dx,@cJxxxx
As usual, we love to bid Majors and bid minors only when we have a very good reason to do so.

Sometimes, you have a better hand than the junky 1@S hand we just saw
^*uWhen you have 9+ points, jump 1 level^*n 
Example: Again, the bidding was 1@h  X  pass   ??
You have @sKJxx   @hxxx   @dxx   @cAJxx.        Jump to 2@s with this hand.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

The arithmetic behind the 9 HCP thing is - when you have 9 + HCP, your side owns the hand .. 
so you announce it to pard, and you may wind up getting to game, even when LHO opened.


1@d - X - pass - 2@d = partner, pick a Major.|
