at|^b@2

Ok .. We have discussed the main kinds of hands and bids you will see when your RHO passes the double.
Some times, RHO will find some kind of bid: a raise of 1@h to 2@h or maybe he bids a new suit or some number of NT
So what do you do when the auction goes     1plum  X  2plums   ??

There is not much of a chance for you to have enough trumps to double for penalty, so the double is "^*uresponsive^*n".
It shows a hand with support for the unbid suits, and depending on the level you are forcing partner to bid at, 
your point count is as follows: 
- If pard can bid at the 2-level, your hand should have a good 6-8 or so, 
- If you are forcing pard to bid at the 3 level, you should have a very good 8 or 9 hcp.
Example:  @sQxxx   @hAxxx   @dxx   @cQJx  
LHO bids   1@d   X   2@d  ?? -- You would double again.
So a responsive double shows support for any suit the doubler would like to bid.
If the auction were   1@s   X    2@s --   you would need a hand like this to double responsively:  
@sxx   @hAxxx   @dKJx   @cQJxx|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


at|

Finally, what does it mean if the partner of the opener (responder) bids some new suit?   Example:  1@c  X  1@S  ??
Now, your double (in Standard bidding) is not responsive. ^*uIt is a penalty double^*n! 
You are showing 4+ spades AND about 9 points.
Here is the logic: 
pard has 13 points (about) and for his double of 1@C, at least 3 spades....right?  You have 4-card "support" for spades
and with 8 or 9 points, you have the balance of strength, too.  So you have the majority of the spades and the majority 
of the points. 
Think the opponents are going to like being in spades?|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|

This also helps you expose the jokester who bids his short suit when he has a big fit for his partner's minor
OK, that is it for this part of the rather complicated topic of bidding after your partner doubles.. 
For a complete discussion of this, there are 3 books I like: 
a) "bridge with bells and whistles, by MaryAnn Dufresne (book of the year, 2010), 
b) Ellen Pomer's book SAYC, which is more for beginners, and finally, 
c) Eddie Kantar's beginner's bidding book..|cp|4|at|IMPROVE YOUR BIDDING SKILLS |
