Wayne_LV:  I fail to see the big deal about 3-card support or 4-card support for a major, if you bid point
count what diff does it make?     Seems like a ton of extra baggage to carry for a small distinction.

mitche: The difference is that a 9-card fit is vastly better than an 8-card fit.  You are "law protected" with a 9-card 
fit to bid to the 3 level... Bergen says that the 9th trump is the most underrated card in the deck!

Wayne_LV:  I realize that but when does it make a diff between bidding game and not bidding game if you have the points?

mitche: When someone doubles, announcing an opening hand and shortness in your bid suit, you can expect a bad trump split, 
Wayne, so that 5-4 fit is crucial in deciding whether to bid to  the 3 or 4 level.
In my experience, bidding to game on an 8 card fit after a double requires something extra.. 

If  I am using BROMAD, I will raise 1@h to 2@h with any 3-card support and any 4-6 point hand.
With 0-3 points, I am not eager to punish pard.  But that 4-card raise to 3 is really, really effective. 
It's almost as disruptive as an opening 3 bid.|
