nt||fp|1|ht|c|cs|2|cp|2|
AT|^b@2

Again, the point I wish to reinforce is to show support immediately when you have 4-card support.

If you have a weak hand with 5-card support and a singleton,
you may ^*upreemptively raise to 4^*n of your pard's Major. 

The last point  I want to make: if you bid a new suit at the 1 level, it is forcing. 
Example:  @sQ10xxx   @hx   @dAxx   @cQJxx  
Bids 1@S when RHO doubles 1@h by your pard
Almost good enough to redouble.

BTW, this is much more frequent when opener starts with 1@c or 1@D.  
And bidding a new suit at the 2 level is non-forcing. 
For instance, over   1@H  (X)
Bid 2@c with @sxx, @hxx, @dQxx, @cKJ10xxx

I think that bidding 2@c here also should show tolerance for your pard's opening 1@H (or 1@S) ... 
So your pard might feel a bit less timid about bidding 2@h with a strong 5-card suit. 
Once again, make sure you and your pard have discussed.

Summary: If you play BROMAD: 
- Raise 1@h or 1@s to 2 with 3 card support and < 6 HCP
- With <6 HCP and 4 card spport, bid 3
- With 7-9 HCP and 3 card support, bid 2@C (BROMAD and ALERTABLE). 
- With 10+ points and  less than 4 card support, redouble (and raise P later with a 3-card support)
- With a limit raise+ and a 4-card support, use JORDAN 2NT
- With 4-card support and 7-9 points, bid 2@D (BROMAD and ALERTABLE)
- Finally with more trumps, (5+) consider a jump raise to 4 (preemptively)

