fp|3|cp|2|cs|1|ht|c|3d|3|at|{^f What to do after a Take-out Double }|
fp|1|cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|
at|^b@2(MM: Some repetition, some new points)
When your partner opens (especially 1 of a Major) and your RHO doubles, it's important to show a fit when you have one.
So if I have a 3-or 4-card fit I will show it. 
An immediate raise says "3 cards and a weakish hand" 
e.g. after 1@S, if I have @sQxx,@hxxx,@DKxxx,@cxxx I raise to 2@s.

How many of you play or know Bergen raises?

So if you play Bergen, this is important: 
After a double of 1@H or 1@S, BERGEN RAISES ARE OFF!!!
Marty invented a convention that he calls "BROMAD" - Bergen Raises Of Major After Double
Here is the idea:

With a "constructive" raise, i.e. 7-9 dummy points, and a double of 1@H or 1@S, 
you use 2@C to show 3 card support and 7-9 dummy points,
And 2@D shows 4 card support and 7-9 dummy points.

Example: @sJxxx,@hKxx,@DKJxx,@cxx
If partner opens 1@H and your RHO doubles, playing BROMAD, you bid 2@C.
If partner opened 1@S, and double on your right, you bid 2@D.

That leaves 1 other case where you want to raise: 
10+ dummy points and a fit  (well, it also leaves the really weak 4 and 5 card raises, and I'll get to them, too) :).
If you happen to have a hand like this: K10xx, xx, Axx, QJxx -- you are too strong for a BROMAD 2@D over 1@S X right? 
So what do you do?|
