If your pard opens 1@C or 1@D and you have a 7 point hand, you should find some action.
Example: pard opens 1@D and RHO doubles - with @sQJxxx,@hxx,@DJxx,@cKxx, I bid 1@S.
You do not promise a 5-card Major, but you do suggest a suit that partner can safely lead from 
(assuming that her holding is not an unsupported Ace, of course!).

And that leaves just one more case: you have a good hand with no good fit for partner
Example:  @sxx,@hAxx,@DKJxx,@cQ10xx
Over  1@S  (X)   your action is to redouble!
Your XX says, "We have the balance of strength" and it suggests very strongly that you are interested in a penalty double
 of anything they bid.. 

If you have a good enough hand to redouble, and your LHO passes your partner will pass with a semi-balanced hand 
and wait for the doubler to rescue himself.  Then you get your penalty X in, most likely.
If opener is unbalanced, he will bid a second suit.

Example: opener has 5-2-3-3 and it goes 1@S  X  XX  pass.
He passes too, and waits for LHO to move.
If doubler passes, you expect to make on brute force.
If doubler guesses to bid partner's 4-card suit, partner should double.
If not, he will pass or bid NT... 

Example: your hand was 5-2-3-3 and doubler reopens with 2@H.
If pard doubles 2@H, it is business. 
If he passes, you are expected to do something clever - 
either double or bid a second suit or NT, if you have hearts stopped.

